05501nam a22007455i 9780813589084DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2019028324  a97808135890847 a10.36019/97808135890842doi  a(DE-B1597)563308  a(OCoLC)1143847371  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aBX9999.G37bM85 2020 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a285.7/794962231 aMulder, Mark T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Glass Church :bRobert H. Schuller, the Crystal Cathedral, and the Strain of Megachurch Ministry /cGerardo Martí, Mark T. Mulder. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (254 p.) :b11 B&W images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tSignificant Dates for Robert Schuller and U.S. Politics, 1945-2015 -- t1. Constituency, Charisma, and Capital -- t2. The Imperative of Church Growth -- t3. Migrants to Orange County, California -- t4. The Possibility Thinker -- t5. No Hippies in the Sanctuary -- t6. Dig a Hole, Schuller -- t7. Always a New Project -- t8. When the Glass Breaks -- tCoda. Ends and Beginnings -- tAppendix: Research Methodology -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRobert H. Schuller's ministry-including the architectural wonder of the Crystal Cathedral and the polished television broadcast of Hour of Power-cast a broad shadow over American Christianity. Pastors flocked to Southern California to learn Schuller's techniques. The President of United States invited him sit prominently next to the First Lady at the State of the Union Address. Muhammad Ali asked for the pastor's autograph. It seemed as if Schuller may have started a second Reformation. And then it all went away. As Schuller's ministry wrestled with internal turmoil and bankruptcy, his emulators-including Rick Warren, Bill Hybels, and Joel Osteen- nurtured megachurches that seemed to sweep away the Crystal Cathedral as a relic of the twentieth century. How did it come to this? Certainly, all churches depend on a mix of constituents, charisma, and capital, yet the size and ambition of large churches like Schuller's Crystal Cathedral exert enormous organizational pressures to continue the flow of people committed to the congregation, to reinforce the spark of charismatic excitement generated by high-profile pastors, and to develop fresh flows of capital funding for maintenance of old projects and launching new initiatives. The constant attention to expand constituencies, boost charisma, and stimulate capital among megachurches produces an especially burdensome strain on their leaders. By orienting an approach to the collapse of the Crystal Cathedral on these three core elements-constituency, charisma, and capital-The Glass Church demonstrates how congregational fragility is greatly accentuated in larger churches, a notion we label megachurch strain, such that the threat of implosion is significantly accentuated by any failures to properly calibrate the inter-relationship among these elements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aBig churches. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aMartí, Gerardo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020z9783110